---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Dancers | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for Dancers working internationally, covering company positions abroad, touring, injury coverage, and professional dance career mobility.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Dancers";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for Dancers practicing abroad, performing with international companies, and building professional dance careers across global stages.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/dancer-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/dancer-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Professional Dance Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Professional dancers perform with ballet companies, modern dance ensembles, musical productions, and commercial shows. They train intensively and perform demanding physical work. Dance careers require exceptional physical conditioning and dedication.
      </p>
      <p>
        International dance careers involve positions with companies abroad, touring productions, and guest engagements worldwide. Dance is a global profession—dancers regularly cross borders for training, auditions, and work. Understanding coverage for the intensive physical demands of dance, international employment, and career-limiting injuries is essential.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for Dancers working abroad across ballet, modern dance, commercial, and independent settings.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Dancers</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'Injury treatment', why: 'High injury rate profession', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Physical therapy', why: 'Ongoing rehabilitation needs', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Orthopedic care', why: 'Joint and skeletal demands', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Body image, career pressure', typical: 'Usually covered' },
          { need: 'Travel medical', why: 'Touring and guest engagements', typical: 'Varies by plan' },
          { need: 'Nutritional support', why: 'Athletic performance demands', typical: 'May be limited' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Injury-Intensive Profession</h3>
      <p>
        Dance has extremely high injury rates. Acute injuries occur during performance and rehearsal. Chronic injuries develop from repetitive demands. Coverage must comprehensively address musculoskeletal health—this is the most critical coverage consideration for dancers.
      </p>
      <p>
        Career-ending injuries are a constant concern. Disability provisions matter for dancers. Rehabilitation coverage affects recovery outcomes. Coverage quality directly impacts career sustainability.
      </p>

      <h3>Company Employment</h3>
      <p>
        Major dance companies provide comprehensive coverage for dancers. Company employment offers the best coverage in the profession. However, company contracts are highly competitive. Many dancers work in settings with less comprehensive coverage.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>Major Ballet Companies</h3>
      <p>
        Elite ballet companies provide excellent benefits. Physical therapy and medical staff are often on-site. Coverage reflects the physical demands of the profession. Major company positions offer the best coverage for dancers.
      </p>

      <h3>Modern Dance Companies</h3>
      <p>
        Modern dance company benefits vary significantly. Well-funded companies provide professional coverage. Smaller companies may have limited provisions. Evaluate company resources carefully.
      </p>

      <h3>Musical Theater</h3>
      <p>
        Broadway and touring musicals include union coverage. AEA and SDC contracts specify provisions. Commercial success affects production resources. Union membership provides contract protections.
      </p>

      <h3>Commercial Dance</h3>
      <p>
        Commercial work—music videos, live tours, corporate events—varies in coverage. Some engagements provide coverage. Others are short-term without benefits. Coverage depends on specific engagement.
      </p>

      <h3>Freelance Dance</h3>
      <p>
        Freelance dancers piece together work from multiple sources. Coverage gaps are common. Individual coverage is essential. Freelance dance careers require careful coverage planning.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Dancers"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Dancers working abroad across ballet, modern dance, and commercial settings."
      buttonText="Compare Dance Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>Training Background</h3>
      <p>
        Professional dancers train intensively from childhood. Conservatory and company school training is common. Training pedigree affects career opportunities. Ballet especially values training lineage.
      </p>

      <h3>Performance Experience</h3>
      <p>
        Auditions evaluate demonstrated ability. Company experience and roles establish credentials. Performance quality determines advancement. Resume of roles and companies matters.
      </p>

      <h3>Union Membership</h3>
      <p>
        AEA, AGMA, and other unions provide professional structure. Union membership affects contract terms. International work may involve different unions. Union membership provides some coverage access.
      </p>

      <h3>International Networks</h3>
      <p>
        Dance is globally connected. Training often includes international study. Company networks cross borders. International experience enhances credentials.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Acute Injuries</h3>
      <p>
        Dance involves constant injury risk. Sprains, strains, and fractures occur. Performance demands don't allow full recovery time. Acute injury treatment is essential coverage.
      </p>

      <h3>Chronic Injuries</h3>
      <p>
        Repetitive demands cause chronic problems. Joint degeneration, tendinitis, and stress fractures develop. Chronic conditions require ongoing management. Coverage must address persistent conditions.
      </p>

      <h3>Mental Health</h3>
      <p>
        Body image pressures are intense in dance. Career uncertainty creates anxiety. Competition and comparison affect wellbeing. Mental health coverage is essential for dancers.
      </p>

      <h3>Eating Disorders</h3>
      <p>
        Dance has elevated eating disorder rates. Aesthetic pressures contribute to disordered eating. Treatment and recovery require specialized care. Coverage should include eating disorder treatment.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>Physical Intensity</h3>
      <p>
        Daily training and rehearsal are physically demanding. Performance adds to physical load. Rest and recovery are limited. Physical demands are the defining feature of dance work.
      </p>

      <h3>Schedule Demands</h3>
      <p>
        Performance schedules are demanding. Touring adds travel fatigue. Technical rehearsals extend hours. Schedule demands compound physical stress.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Uncertainty</h3>
      <p>
        Dance careers are short and uncertain. Competition for positions is intense. Injury can end careers suddenly. Career uncertainty is constant.
      </p>

      <h3>Body Image Pressure</h3>
      <p>
        Physical appearance is professionally evaluated. Weight and body shape affect casting. Pressure around bodies is ongoing. Mental health support addresses body image stress.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>International Opportunities</h3>
      <p>
        Companies worldwide hire dancers. European companies often offer better contracts than US companies. Training abroad develops skills. Coverage must accommodate global career possibilities.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Length</h3>
      <p>
        Dance careers are shorter than most professions. Physical demands limit career span. Transition planning is essential. Coverage for career transitions matters.
      </p>

      <h3>Transition Planning</h3>
      <p>
        Dancers must plan for post-performance careers. Teaching, choreography, and arts administration are common paths. Education during dance careers prepares for transitions. Career transition support is valuable.
      </p>

      <h3>Post-Career Health</h3>
      <p>
        Dance careers leave lasting physical effects. Joint problems and chronic pain continue after retirement. Coverage for long-term effects matters. Health planning extends beyond performing years.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm joining a company abroad. What coverage should I expect?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Major international companies typically provide comprehensive coverage. European companies often have excellent social benefits. Verify specific coverage before accepting contracts. Physical therapy and medical care access are essential.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I was injured during performance. What coverage applies?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Performance injuries should be covered by company insurance. Document injuries thoroughly. Workers' compensation may apply depending on jurisdiction. Follow company injury protocols while seeking treatment.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I work freelance between company contracts. How do I maintain coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Freelance periods create coverage gaps. Individual international health insurance provides continuity. Union benefits may provide some gap coverage. Coverage continuity is essential for injury-prone professions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm struggling with body image issues. What support exists?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Body image challenges are common in dance. Use mental health coverage proactively. Specialists who understand dance and eating disorders exist. Seek help early—these issues worsen without treatment.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I have a chronic injury affecting my dancing. What coverage addresses this?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Chronic injuries require ongoing management. Coverage should include physical therapy and specialist care. Work with medical professionals who understand dancers. Manage chronic conditions proactively to extend career.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm considering career transition. What coverage considerations matter?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Career transition affects coverage significantly. Plan coverage continuity during transition. Post-dance health needs continue—joint problems and chronic conditions persist. Maintain coverage for ongoing physical needs after performing career ends.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by understanding your coverage situation based on employment type. Company employment provides the most comprehensive coverage. Freelance dancers need individual coverage strategies. Injury coverage is the most critical consideration for all dancers.
      </p>
      <p>
        Dance creates powerful live experiences and expresses human movement art. Your coverage should support this demanding profession—comprehensively addressing injury risk, enabling international career mobility, and planning for sustainable health throughout and beyond performing careers.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Dance Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Dancers working abroad across ballet, modern dance, and commercial settings."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
